segments.text: There's one with a government job in aid, and another one with an architect engineer firm out of Houston.
It would have been engineering and construction side of aid to foreign countries.
And sure enough, I ended up on the list being promoted to colonel.
And I went in and told Mr. Turner that I was not going to be able to accept the promotion of the Colonel, that I planned to retire, and that I had told him about it, and that I would get down.
Well, that was worse than hitting a beehive with a stick, because a hell of a lot of effort had been put in to
make damn sure, I guess, that I'd been promoted.
You just don't go around and say, hey, we ought to promote something.
Sure.
And so we didn't speak for a couple of days.
And then when we finally got back to speaking, he said, now you've got to wait a minute, boss.
You told me I don't have to do anything but pay taxes and die.
I'm getting out.
He said, well, what would it take for you to stay in?
I said, well, you know, I'm a reserve officer.
He said, you either get that enigma off my back where I'm an indefinite reserve and I can go as long as I want to go, or I want to be in the record.
Why aren't you in the record now?
I said, I've been selected three times and each time they ruled me out because of my eyes.
Okay.
Two days later he came back and he said, you're taking a physical out of Andrew?
Yeah.
He said, well, they've marked that thing out.
It no longer says retirement fiscal.
It says appointment fiscal.
You're going to be appointed into the regular Air Force.
I said, well, I'm curious how that happened.
He says, well, when this thing came to the secretary, he didn't hesitate to say, hell, I'll ask the Surgeon General to waive his eyesight.
And here's the letter he sent the Surgeon General, and here's the letter back from the Surgeon General.
He says, they waived your eyesight.
He says, you're in the regular.
I said, OK.
So they're in the regulars and you're full colonel.
Well, I could do the grade full colonel because I accepted the promotion.
But because of a lot of personnel thing that would take a long time to explain, my permit grade was major.
See?
Well, ultimately it caught up, got up the colonel.
But because of a certain thing, my permit grade was major.
But that didn't hurt because then I could retire on,
what I was wearing on my shoulders.
Sure.
Okay.
Okay.
The very next thing that happens is, well, you know, the minute I got you promoted, I knew I had to lose you, so you're going to have to go overseas.
I said, yep, I've already got my orders.
What do you mean you got your orders?
I said, well, I've got an alert.
Where are you going?
I said, I'm going to Thailand.
What the hell are you going to do in Thailand?
I said, I'm going to be the number one engineer over there.
He said, I'm going to be responsible for all those bases you and I have been visiting and worked with the Navy whenever we have to have.
Oh, you're not going to do that.
Does Goddard know about this?
Well, this was General Goddard, who then had replaced Curtin as the top engineer in the Air Force.
By the way, General Goddard's picture hangs on the wall over there at the former student.
But he is a
He was a West Point graduate, got his master's at A&M, but now he lives in North Carolina.
So you can't reach him.
Yeah, but anyway, this is the Goddard that had been in there a couple of times.
I worked for him at the Aviation Engineer Force, went down to North Africa to work for him, and now here Goddard is again.
I said, no, he doesn't know anything about it.
He said, you get me on the phone.
Get him on the phone.
So they got together and said, you're not going to Thailand.
I said, well, where am I going?
you know Project Anglo House?
I said, yeah.
You mean building those 1,500 houses over in the United Kingdom?
Yeah.
He said, you're going to the United Kingdom.
I said, who in the hell wants to go build 1,500 houses?
You do.
Yes, sir.
So off we go to England.
This means the third time that I've been stationed in England.
War, and then once before, and twice now that she goes
But we go to England.
Well, wasn't that a more desirable duty in England than Thailand?
Well, who knew how long the Vietnam-Thailand thing was going on?
Sure.
And an old army general said, we ain't got but one more, and everybody wants to get in it.
Well, OK. Yeah, it was a good job.
Got over there, and we had these 1,500 houses that were to be built, all of them to be

individually owned by a British entrepreneur, not owned by our own government, which meant that they bought the land, they designed the house, we approved the design, we oversaw the construction, and then when the house was finished, they owned it, but we guaranteed occupancy for a five-year period.
With American military personnel?
Yeah.
Remember I said earlier, we built 200 of them up in Scotland for the Navy.
to support the polarity.
Then we also had an intelligence project that was over the horizon radar.
It was built up on the coast and it was, we did the facility work and RCA was at the same time we were building, supposed to be
trying to develop the system that would be installed there, and it's just what it says, over the horizon radar.
Well, how did that work?
Well, it didn't.
We finished the facility, and we put in all the antenna, built all the buildings, put in all the shielding.
The thing was actually constructed on ground elevation zero, which meant that we had the
elevate the buildings.
The roads were down on zero, but the buildings were up on piling 16 feet above the ground.
But anyway, the RCA never got the system perfected to go in there.
And the facility is standing right now just as a monument.
You might say it's stupidity, but it was a, what do you call, you build while we're developing.
It didn't seem like a very good idea.
It was a combination of American and British funded.
Our job was with the British engineers and constructors to get it built by a certain time date.
And I got to- Where was it built?
I beg your pardon?
Where was it and where was it built?
Okay, there are two bases right up on the coast called Bentwater's Woodbridge.
And if you drew an angle, I mean, a line off of each one of them about
each flying ahead in the east a little bit.
It would cross at a place called Orford Ness.
And again, it's on the coast, zero elevation.
It was an old World War I bombing range.
We had to go in there and clear the mines and all the bombs out before we could ever get started.
I got a handpick of a major that I made lieutenant colonel, and he has retired as a colonel, too.
oversee the thing, and an outstanding job.
But, well, my job didn't, I went over on a three-year assignment, and I didn't get to stay for two years.
My boss, who was John Bell, came back from a promotion board and called me in one day and said, type your gear, you're fired.
I said, you've got to be kidding me.
He said, nope.
You're leaving.
Can you tell me where I'm going?
He said, yeah, you're going to Germany.
You're going to Wiesbach.
Well, that was headquartered in Air Force Europe, which was the next headquarters higher.
I said, OK. What am I going to do over there?
He said, you're going to be the top engineer.
I said, well, what's happened to Jim?
He said, Jim's already agreed to go.
He's had three chances to make general, and he hasn't made it, so he's agreed to quit.
Who is Jim?
Jim Finlan, Colonel Finlan, was sitting in the chair over there.
So he was the chief engineer over there?
Yeah.
He went to Germany the same year I went to England.
We went over on the ship together, on the United States, by the way.
Jim had had one chance in Pentagon, two chances in Germany, and wasn't selected, so he said, I'll back out.
So he was resigning, or retiring?
Yeah.
And...
So I went over and I said, OK, I guess so.
And he says, there's no guessing about it.
It's already set up.
You're going over.
You're it.
And so I just went over and didn't do anything different.
Just kept right on working and doing whatever had to be done.
So your job in Germany was to be the engineer then.
for the entire Air Force of all of Europe.
That must have been a tremendous responsibility.
See, he had been there two years as a colonel and didn't make general.
So I went in there and it was my intention to stay until the tour was over and then come home and retire.
How long do you stay in the service?
MR. Sure.
And we were relaxing one afternoon, getting ready to go to a party that night, and General Holzapfel, the four-star, called and he said  I said, yes, sir.
And he said, this is Randy.
I said, yes, sir.
He said, in one hour, the President will nominate this year's list of
new Brigadier General to the Senate, and I want to let you know that you're on that list.
What did you feel like?
And I had been going retirement homes, and I just threw them up in the air.
And she looked at me, and she said, are you on the General's list?
I said, yeah.
She said, what do you think?
I said, oh, it'll be worse than ever now.
Because it is, and I knew it was.
The colonel has a lot of power.
The general has absolutely none.
Why do you say that?
Well, you go where they tell you to go.
You say what they tell you to say.
You do what they tell you to do.
And you just got a little more limitation

the type of conduct or what and i'm sure you've heard the phrase and it's true it's lonesome it really is why subordinates don't come up and socially social you know associated you make your own social life
You either go out and socialize with other general officers, and hell, there may not be any others.
Or you reach down and try to pick a few colonels, and they may not want to socialize with you.
It's a different life altogether when you cross that line.
Altogether.
A colonel can be given a job that no matter what you think about it, he can say, you know, that thing could be, a major could do that job.
And we realize, colonel, but we want you to do it, you know.
You've got the qualifications.
We've got to get this job done.
Or he can sit in this job that the table of organization calls for a brigadier general.
But he's still a colonel.
You know, and he's looked at.
He's a colonel.
You cross that damn line, everybody's
You're under scrutiny.
And you've also got one other thing.
When the next list comes along, you know, the next promotion list, the pressure is on for you to get out.
Because they can't promote that guy that's on this list until you make a vacancy.
So of all the existing generals, after they get 60 up down here waiting, the pressure is on.
We've got to get these guys promoted before the end of the year so we can put another 60 on the list.
So the pressure is on.
You think about retiring?
Every once in a while they're like, hey, you think about retiring?
That's what people would say to you?
Oh, sure.
What type of people?
I mean, personnel people.
Personnel people.
But anyway.
Well, what did you answer when they asked you?
Are you thinking about retiring?
No, not yet.
Not yet.
Not for a while.
Now, like I said, they come out with this list, and the Senate approves it, and then as the vacancy comes, you step up.
Certainly.
So here it was in Christmas, the list came out, and I went to New Year's Day, not the next year, but one whole year before I ever got off the list and changed Eagle to a star.
One year.
Waiting for a job.
That's right.
No, not for a job.
Just an opening.
I had a job.
I stayed there.
So you were waiting for somebody else to retire.
That's right.
I stayed there.
When I left, still didn't have an opening.
Went to the log command in Ohio, and I was there six months before an opening came.
They gave me the promotion.
That's true all over the Air Force.
Now, the Army and the Navy, they don't do it that way, but the Air Force.
Well, how do they do it now?
I don't know.
I don't know.
I don't know when they make the decision, but there's a term called frocking.
They let a guy change the insignia on his shoulder, but he doesn't get paid until the vacancy occurs because Congress is limited because of appropriation.
But a guy may be wearing something in the Army and the Navy, but he's still being paid something different.
Every once in a while the Air Force will truck somebody, especially if they're going to go overseas and work for the foreign government.
And if he's on a promotion list, they'll let him go ahead and change his signal.
But if he's working with his own people, they don't truck him.
Never got into wire.
what the reasoning is, whether good or bad or whatever.
It sounds to me then that you went from being promoted to a full colonel to a brigadier general in just two years.
Yep, that's about right.
Well, that's extraordinarily fast.
How can you count for that?
I had people that believed in me.
I had people that were, you know, you'd call them
They were my sponsor.
The one, I guess, that bleed in me the most was Mr. Turner.
The vice commander of Air Force Europe was a three-star gentleman by the name of George Simler, who is deceased.

General Bell, the commander of the 3rd Air Force, that I was working for there in England, was quite impressed with what we were doing and what I was able to get done working through and with the British.
And then General Goddard, who was the director of civil engineering, the top engineer in the Air Force, who I had worked for at the Aviation Engineering Force,

quite aware of what I could do and so on and I guess I have to say those poor gentlemen were probably responsible for seeing that General Holden was convinced that I would be promoted and of course by him recommending if he hadn't recommended me I would never have made it because any Air Force
All the recommendations come in from the commanders of what we call the major commands.
They all come to a very big pool.
And then a group of general officers review these people.
And they reduce the total that had come in down to some agreed upon figure, like three for every one to be selected.
Remember I said my General Bell had come back from a promotion board.
He sat on that board the year before I made it.
That's the reason he knew the other guy hadn't made it and wasn't going to make it because he didn't even get by that board.
From here, whatever it's agreed upon that year, it may be, okay, we're going to promote 60, put 180 to the last board.
Or it may be put 120 to the last board.
It reduces the amount of effort to the last board.
So you've got to get out of command, you've got to get past this board, and then you've got to be selected by that last one.
And the last one is a bunch of four stars that are sitting there.
You all but say, how in the hell?
How did I do it?
I'm not told.
Anybody ask me, what do you think?
I'm one grade higher than I ever expected to be.
If I'd have done it, don't ask me how I did it.
And yet, that's what I tell them publicly or what.
Whenever my subordinates would come to me, my military supporters, not civilians, come to me and say, I've got to make out my career sheet.
The Air Force has got a personnel thing to keep having here.
Junior year officers make out.
What do you want to do next?
When do you want to go to school and so on?
Service is one.
When you leave here and I leave here, I thought maybe I'd like to do showing something.
Sounds pretty good.
That's something you haven't done and you want to experience.
Then I thought I'll go to school.
What kind of?
Oh, squadron officers.
What do you want to go there for?
Well, I ought to get it on my records that I've been to school.
After that, the school would show up again.
I said, where are you going to get all those school spots?
You've got to get them on your record.
I said, well, maybe.
I said, you know, the pendulum swings back and forth, and you've got to watch that pendulum.
If you've got a whole bunch of people in personnel or at the top that are saying, go to school, go to school, and by all means, get school on your record.
Remember, you can take it back to our spotters.
And I can remember one of these guys thinking, he said, General, what schools have you been to?
I said, I went to Adjutant General School six weeks.
I went to Academic Instructor School six weeks.
I went to a school to learn how to be an Inspector General two weeks.
I went to the Atomic Defense Construction Course for maybe two weeks.
I said, I've been to four schools.
What do you do the other time?
Work.
I said, and I work for other people, not for other Air Force engineers if I cannot help it.
I work for civilians that have gotten power.
I work for other branches of the service.
Work for the Army.
Work with the Navy.
Somebody else is writing that ticket.
And try to be sure that it's not somebody that you're competing with that's writing your ticket.
Somebody that's not going to say, boy, if I build him up too great, he's going to pass me in.
I never thought about that.
But work, production is the key.
We're not in this service to go to school.
We're not in this service to do anything but remember.
The Air Force mission is to fly and to fight, and it's up to you as an engineer to keep the facilities available so that they can fly and fight.
Not go to school.
Well, you have to admit that your career was rather unusual.
I've interviewed a number of generals, and they have command schools and more colleges on their record.
Most of them say in Stanley that they were very valuable experiences.
That's right.
You see, down the line, you're going to get me back under another civilian.
I have worked under two GS-18s.
And I'll bet you that you can find very, very few that ever worked for civilians.
Most of the time they've been working for other military.
But I worked for two civilians, and I convinced one of them I could produce, and that was Turner's.
I know that Turner got me promoted to colonel, and I know damn good and well he was partially responsible for getting me promoted to colonel.
So your years in the Pentagon were really the key then?
Sure.
Just think, I could have gone to ROTC for the second time.
Yeah.
And then you would have retired as lieutenant colonel probably.
That's right.
Yep.
Well, let's talk about Germany here, 1970-1971.
This is a tremendous responsibility as the chief engineer for the Air Force in Europe.
Did you have any major problems?
Problems?
No.
Challenges?
Sure.
What were some of the challenges?
Well, we had our fighters dispersed, of course, on base.
We were now putting them in hardened shelters.
And again, under the concurrency concept, we were putting them in hardened shelters, but the shelters didn't have any doors on them.
And so while we were erecting and building the shelters on the continent, they were testing the different proposed doors back here in the United States.
They finally approved the design of one.
And the company that won the contract was a company by the name of Marway Steel.
And they established a plant in Luxembourg, which was just across the border from here.
And they manufactured and fabricated the doors and then brought them up and installed them and so on.
And these shelters were designed to withstand like a nuclear blast?
Well, not a direct nuke.
No, of course not.
But they were principally designed against just a high explosion.
When you start designing against nuclear, you're just making it too costly to protect one bird, one aircraft.
These were above ground.
Oh yeah, above ground.
And armor plated doors.
They, well, you just don't go through something of that magnitude without having different challenges.
What else besides, did you finish those?
Oh yeah, we finished them.
So now we have these shelters at every air base?
In Germany.
Oh, in Germany?
Yeah, not in England.
Okay.
Then we were bringing the F-111 in to England.
And, of course, we had been working on that while I was over there in England.
And, of course, it wasn't yet completed.
That's the one place that we did have to...
come up with new stories because what we had had in there before then was reconnaissance type aircraft, not bombers.
So we had the new problems there.
How did you resolve those?
Well, just lots of meetings with British people and British agencies and so on.
Were the British still sympathetic to having nuclear warheads?
The government was.
Of course, some of the people in the countryside.
That's good old farmland that you're taking away from us.
Let's see, the heart shelters,
The chief staff of the Air Force in Washington, General Ryan, I had briefed General Ryan a number of times.
In fact, I had briefed him on the F-111 move and so on.
And General Ryan lives here in San Antonio now.
But he issued a policy that said,
I want all headquarters moved to an air base, an air force base.
An air force base, by definition, means you've got a runway.
I don't want anything, industrial complex or something like that, move everything.
He said, I want my people to be able to smell jet fuel.
How are you going to think?
flying, unless you see flying, unless you hear flying, and that was it.
When I got to Wiesbaden, Germany, General Holzapfel called me in.
He says, General Ryan says we're going to move to Ramstein.
I said, all right.
I said, I'll get down there and check the facilities out and so on.
He said, wait a minute, wait a minute.
More than that, I said, what's that?
And he says, normally a move like this would be planned and written by ops plans or a planning program, somebody like that.
He said, they've been fiddling around with this thing for over a year.
They're finding a thousand reasons why this headquarters can't be moved to Ramstein.
Yes, I could hear it coming.
He says, you will write the plan to move this headquarters to Ramstein.
Well, that's not really an engineer's job.
Our job is to support it, to determine what facilities are needed, crank it into the plan, and everything.
He says, don't come back and tell me why we can't go.
Come back to the plan that says how we will go.
He says, now, I realize I realize you're just a colonel.
You're going to knock heads with a two-star general over there, and you're going to knock heads with a one-star general over there.
But you just stay with it.
I will announce the assignment tomorrow morning at the staff meeting, and I'll expect your full cooperation.
We wrote the plan.
Headquarters is now in Ramstein.
And it moved.
Did you have problems with your one- and two-star generals?
Not when he says they're writing a plan.
It's not why we can't move.
It's how we're going to move.
That was it.
But I didn't know that they'd been messing around with it for a year and a half.
Sure, over in England, we keep hearing, hey, the headquarter's got to move the ramps.
Never happened.
Never happened.
Sure enough, he never came up with a plan.
He just come up with a plan.
He just gave you the responsibility.
Yeah, that was it.
Of course I had to find me some people in my own staff that could work on such a plant because that's not our daily work.
But we did it and he moved.
We had a real good guy that wasn't there very long and that was Jay Robin.
He was I guess
I don't guess we even overlapped.
He was in there, and somebody had taken his job by the time I got there.
But I mentioned this at breakfast this morning to another retired Air Force general about your experience with Jay and spending two days with him.
And he said, why didn't you tell him to spend 30 years with him like we did?
He used to be the inspector general.
That's a hell of a time.
Another interesting thing, following the war, they established an organization of civilians called the General Service Unit.
And it was made up of Germans, Turks, Italians,
few Spanish, and it had one Air Force officer as its advisor.

The whole thing was set up on a military organization, but they were all civilians, and they were all from the different nationalities that were just wandering around Europe trying to find a place, abbreviated the GSU.
That unit did various jobs of construction.
Most of the design we did in our own staff, then gave them the job.
Anywhere we told them to go.
Put them on a job in Turkey, lay a pipeline across the river, something like that.
And they did jobs that
had to be done in a hurry, that we couldn't take the time to go out to bid for, or it may be a job just to keep them occupied in order to keep the unit in being.
And it was located at one of the bases, and I had a captain that was, believe it or not, a captain, not very much, but he was part of it.
Most of the captains we put there were sharp guys, and they were their advisors.
And any time they have a problem with our staff back at the headquarters, we'll lose up to the captain to wade in and help get the problem solved.
But we use that unit all over Europe and into Turkey.
It wasn't a case of election when one of their
People that might say it was an officer level either left or died or retired or something like that.
And the captain would come back to the boss, whoever's sitting in my chair, and say, OK, now we've got to decide who we're going to promote up.
And they were organized along the military line, even though they were civilians.
They had their own camp, their own dining halls, everything.
The Air Force now has a number of units
that were copied from that organization, but they are military organizations.
Why'd you only stay at this job for one year, 1970 and 1971?
When you are a Brigadier General,
or any kind of gun in the airport.
When the chief of staff tells you to go over there and do that job, you say, yes, sir, or else you say, here's my badge.
The General Holzapfel left as commander of USAID, of Air Force Europe.
And General Jones, who is now the chairman of the Joint Chief,
commander of USAFD.
And he had a protege by the name of Bob Thompson that had been his engineer when he was a SAC commander at the base over in Louisiana.
And he wanted Thompson to be his engineer.
And it was as simple as that.
He just tells the person, tells the general assignment officer, I want Thompson to come in.
Now it's up to the general assignment to start, OK, what happens now?
So this, remember I used the name McGarvey, was the engineer in the air staff when we were building Tuiwa.
He got promoted from colonel to general.
OK, he's now sitting out it.
Air Force Logistics Command at Wright-Patterson, and he's been out there for a number of years, and it's about time that he would have an overseas assignment.
So they picked McGarvey up, sent him overseas, and okay, you go in and take McGarvey's place at Wright-Patterson.
Did you get an opportunity to meet General Jones?
General Jones?
Oh, yeah.
What was your impressions of him?
Oh...
I never...
I never really tried to draw to develop an analysis and say, what kind of guy we got here.
When I knew him, he was in a very, very difficult position to say, this is the real guy.
Because he was sitting as General Holzapfel's deputy.
wearing three stars, but he knew that he was going to be the commander in just one, two, or three months.
And that's a real bad time because, man, you're trying already to get things straightened out, to run the way you want them, you're trying to get your staff, you know, like
General Goddard and I were in there in his office.
General Goddard, again, is out of Washington.
He came over and paid a visit.
Out of courtesy, he said, well, I better go see Joan.
When we walked out, Joan says, hey, guy, Goddard.
He says, get Bob Thompson over here to be Hub's deputy, because when Hub leaves, I want him to be my engineer.
So two steps out in the hall, I turned to Goddard, and I said, where am I going?
He said, that's the first I heard, that you're going.
Four stars have got that much power.
And they should have.
How did that make you feel, though?
I went to Texas A&M.
I've been exposed to a lot of things.
I just turned to the director of engineering and, well, it looks like I'm going.
Where am I going?
Because I knew I'd already been to the charm schools.
They went here on that promotion list.
Immediately, boy, they bring all the new
Selectees in, and we go through what's called a charm school for a whole week in Washington.
Tell me about that.
Oh, yeah.
We're lectured to.
Is this in all services?
No, this is Air Force.
OK.
But we are lectured to by the chief of staff of all of the services, the commandant of the Marines, the chief of staff of the Army.
Westmoreland talked to us.
He talked to us and used every bit of his time and left no time for questions.
We knew what was happening.
Hell, we were loaded for it.
Ran out of time.
But anyway, all of the chiefs talked to us, and then we get certain rules that are laid down to us, you know, verbally, and then we get certain advice.
Well, what kind of things do they tell you for this week?
All colonels designate generals.
That's right.
Okay, and what do they tell you?
What's expected of you as a general officer is what I was addressing a while ago.
Instead of, you're no longer a colonel, you're a general officer.
You've got more eyes watching you now than ever have watched you before.
What you do in the public will be known, if it's wrong tomorrow, all over the world.
Well, you can say these things in a hurry, but they're told to you from time to time as you're there and they talk about public relations.
What other topics besides public relations?
Probably getting along with Congress and stuff like that.
Oh, yeah.
The director of legislative liaison comes in and says, now, I know that some of you have never been on the Hill.
Some of you have probably had more time on the Hill than I have.
And lay it out.
Then you will have a protocol-type dinner or lunch in which
OK, now, let's go through some protocol.
And it's just a wrap-up of everything you ought to know before you get out there and stump your toes.
Sure.
